5/1/00
  Got a version of statmux from Matt (statmux1001.fls) which will not move
  PCR back, but instead flush pictures.


5/2/00
  Trying to solve the hanging when DPI detect video stopped:
    Once RC is halted, output task will not be able to send out further
    TPs.  Hence we need to use a higher input halt threshold than
    rc halt threshold.

    Noticed that even input and rc are halted, free PidBuf still decrease
    to 0 because PidBufs are used to store RATECONVERT messages from
    statmux.

    We must make sure that RC of a frame can continue.  Otherwise there
    will be no way to release any TPs.  This means that INPUT_HALT_THRES
    must be significantly larger than RC_HALT_THRES, so that the gap is
    big enough to hold the biggest output picture.
     
  Try stealing pictures:
    Seems to be not causing any accumulation problem. 
    Seems to be quite effective in avoid input/RC halt.
    Problem: need to set an on and off threshold to avoid bouncing.


5/3/00
  The problem with picture stealing is that during the stealing period,
  the effective input rate to statmux is reduced.  As a result, statmux
  is not aware of this fact and schedule the output at a lower channel rate.
  After stealing period is over, the input rate is back high up and in
  a short period of time the statmux stacks up the pictures and force
  DPI to go into another stealing period.  


5/4/00
  Looked at GI's DCT1000 setop box problem.  SeaChange reported that the
  top part of the video frame is distorted with the GI setop box decoder.
  We noticed that this is probably due to a problem in the setop box which
  cannot handle clean cut source.  We can reproduce the problem with the
  DiviCom source (clean cut), with either dpi, bitshaper or simply Jinbo's
  bypass diagnostic codes.

  One way to verify the above observation, and solve the problem at the same
  time is to destroy the cleanCut property in the output process:
    - In Splicer, increment no. of TP for each picture by 1 to account for
      additional TP.
    - At Output, chop off portion of the last TP of a picture, and mix it with
      the next picture's PES. 
  Created a separete task, ytse-gi_setop for this test.

  Topics for discussion:
      SeaChange reported occasional frame reversal problem after the switch.
      (We suspect SeaChange uses the SA decoder.)
      (Possibly due to missing of seq end code in the net->ad switch!)

      Gap issue: Whether SeaChange is going to do something about it, or
      we need to handle it anyway.
      (Filling gap with black frames may be a reasonable alternative.)

